{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 16:39:47.724243", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report — enterprise OSPF network, HTTP service via nginx load balancer\n\nScope and approach\n- I checked end-to-end reachability across hosts, servers and the load balancer, tested HTTP from representative clients, inspected the load-balancer process/config and network configuration, and exercised backend reachability from the LB.\n- Focus: detect anomalies, localize affected devices, and identify likely root causes. No mitigations are proposed here.\n\nExecutive summary / overall health\n- Control-plane and routing appear healthy: wide set of ICMP tests (host-to-host, infra-to-host, server-to-host) show 0% packet loss and low/consistent RTTs (single-digit ms). DHCP and DNS are functioning for client hosts (hosts obtained addresses and resolve web99.local).\n- The HTTP service (web99.local) is reachable from client hosts and returns HTTP 200, so end-to-end service availability is present.\n- There are two notable issues/anomalies that require attention:\n  1. Load balancer DNS/name resolution: the load balancer cannot resolve web99.local locally.\n  2. Performance anomaly: HTTP response timing (TTFB and total) from clients shows unexpectedly high latency (~0.28–0.48 s TTFB, ~1.08–1.28 s total) compared to the sub-5 ms network RTTs — indicates application/proxy/backend latency rather than network loss.\n\nEvidence and findings (detailed)\n1) Network connectivity and routing\n- Reachability sweep: multiple ping tests across the lab show 0% packet loss; typical RTTs in the 1–4 ms range (examples in the test matrix). This implies OSPF routing and IP forwarding are operating correctly across cores, distribution and server-access router(s).\n- Ping from a client to the load balancer: host_1_2_1_1 -> 10.200.0.7 average ~3.86 ms (4 replies, 0% loss). Healthy.\n\n2) DNS / name resolution\n- From client hosts:\n  - getent hosts web99.local -> 10.200.0.7 (hosts correctly resolve web99.local to the LB IP).\n- From the load balancer host:\n  - getent hosts web99.local returned no entry (empty).\n  - curl -siS http://web99.local -H 'Host: web99.local' from the LB returned HTTP code 000 (DNS/name resolution failure when LB tries to resolve the name itself).\n- However, the LB can be reached by its IP and accepts connections; clients’ DNS is working for them, but the LB lacks the same resolution for the name. This is an operational inconsistency (LB lacks DNS resolution for the service name).\n\n3) Load balancer (nginx) configuration and state\n- Process listening: ss shows nginx listening on 0.0.0.0:80 on the load balancer.\n- nginx.conf (on load_balancer) contains an upstream block:\n    upstream web99 {\n        server 20.200.0.2:80;\n        server 20.200.0.3:80;\n        server 20.200.0.4:80;\n    }\n  and a server block proxy_pass http://web99;\n- Network interfaces on load balancer:\n  - eth0: 10.200.0.7/24 (facing client/service network)\n  - eth1: 20.200.0.1/24 (facing backends)\n- Observations:\n  - nginx is bound and functional (LB responds to curl by IP/Host header).\n  - The upstream uses the 20.200.0.0/24 addresses (on eth1), consistent with the LB having a 20.200.0.1 address on eth1.\n\n4) Backend reachability from LB\n- From LB:\n  - curl 20.200.0.2 -> HTTP 200 (backend responds when addressed on 20.200.0.x).\n  - ping to web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) and to web_server_1/2 -> all reachable with low RTTs (~1–2 ms).\n  - curl to 10.200.0.7 (LB IP) with Host header success 200 (shows nginx handles host header correctly).\n- Note: inventory lists web_server_x as 10.200.0.3..6; nginx upstream uses 20.200.0.2..4. The LB has addresses on both 10.200.0.x (eth0) and 20.200.0.x (eth1). There are reachable endpoints at 20.200.0.x that respond 200 when contacted (so some backend addresses exist in that subnet). This indicates dual addressing/segmentation is in use; it is a potential source of confusion but the LB can reach its configured upstreams.\n\n5) HTTP performance measurements (from clients)\n- curl from host_1_2_1_1 to http://web99.local (5 runs):\n  - name lookup/connect times very small (ms), but starttransfer values ~0.28–0.32 s, total times ~1.11s (one run started transfer at ~0.476 s and total ~1.28 s).\n- curl from host_2_1_1_2 to http://web99.local (5 runs):\n  - starttransfer ~0.285–0.321 s, total ~1.08–1.10 s (consistent, lower variance than the other host).\n- Interpretation:\n  - Network RTTs are small (<5 ms), yet the time to first byte (TTFB / starttransfer) is ~280–320 ms consistently. This is far larger than the network layer latency and indicates delay at application layer: either nginx proxying behavior (establishing upstream connections, retries, connection timeouts or upstream slow responses), or back-end web application processing delay.\n  - The one outlier with starttransfer ~0.476 s suggests occasional longer backend processing or a connection setup event (e.g., upstream connection creation rather than keep-alive reuse).\n\n6) Local name resolution mismatch on LB\n- The LB itself cannot resolve web99.local (getent empty), so commands on the LB that refer to the name will fail DNS resolution (curl returned 000). This is not stopping clients because they resolve via central DNS. It is an operational deficiency on the LB host.\n\nLocalization of the issues / implicated devices\n- Load_balancer\n  - Confirmed running nginx and accepting connections.\n  - DNS resolution absent on the LB (can't resolve web99.local locally) — configuration inconsistency on the LB host (missing DNS/hosts entry).\n  - Nginx upstream configured for 20.200.0.2..4 and LB has eth1 20.200.0.1 — LB’s upstream addresses are reachable from the LB.\n  - LB is strongly implicated as the focal point of the HTTP performance behavior (it proxies client requests to upstreams).\n- Backend web servers\n  - Backends are reachable from the LB (ICMP and curl to 20.200.0.2 returned 200), but their IP addressing in the inventory (10.200.0.x) differs from the upstream addresses (20.200.0.x). Backends could be contributing to slow response times (application latency).\n- Core/distribution routers, DNS server, DHCP server\n  - Reachability and name resolution from clients are functioning (clients get DHCP addresses and DNS resolves web99.local to LB IP). Routers and infrastructure appear healthy based on the reachability data.\n\nLikely root cause(s) and hypotheses\n1) Application/proxy latency (primary hypothesis)\n- The consistent ~280–320 ms TTFB seen by clients, while network RTTs are ~1–4 ms, strongly indicates that the delay is happening at the application layer — either:\n  - Nginx is spending time establishing/negotiating connections to upstream backends (e.g., upstream connection establishment cost, DNS lookup by LB for upstream hostnames if configured as names — but nginx.conf uses IPs so DNS lookup for upstreams is not required), or\n  - The upstream web servers are taking ~0.3 s to generate the first byte (backend processing delay), or\n  - Nginx is attempting an upstream that is slow/unavailable causing retries/timeouts before using a healthy backend (would produce higher variance or larger spikes).\n- Evidence: LB → backends ping and curl succeed with low RTT; curl to upstream IP from LB returned 200 (but we did not measure backend TTFB directly from LB). The consistency of ~0.3 s suggests a systematic delay (e.g., backend app startup work, connection setup cost, or proxy buffering).\n\n2) Operational/configuration inconsistencies\n- The load balancer lacks the same DNS resolution context as clients (cannot resolve web99.local locally). This is an operational inconsistency (LB cannot self-query the same name); could cause scripts or healthchecks on LB to misbehave or to fallback to undesirable behavior.\n- Upstream IP space mismatch vs. inventory: inventory/listing shows web servers at 10.200.0.x, while nginx upstream uses 20.200.0.x. The LB has an interface in 20.200.0.0/24 so this is probably intentional (separate backend VLAN). Still, the different addressing between documented server addresses (10.200.0.x) and upstream addresses (20.200.0.x) is a source of confusion and risk of misconfiguration.\n\n3) Not a primary network-layer fault\n- No packet loss, routing seems correct, DNS and DHCP for clients are functional. No anomalies observed at IP forwarding level.\n\nActionable observations (evidence list)\n- get_reachability: extensive ping matrix — 0% loss across many pairs; small RTTs.\n- Client curl stats (host_1_2_1_1 and host_2_1_1_2) to http://web99.local: starttransfer ~0.28–0.32 s and total ~1.08–1.28 s.\n- On load_balancer:\n  - ss shows nginx listening on :80\n  - cat /etc/nginx/nginx.conf shows upstream servers listed as 20.200.0.2..4 and proxy_pass http://web99;\n  - ip addr: eth0 10.200.0.7/24, eth1 20.200.0.1/24\n  - getent hosts web99.local -> empty (LB cannot resolve name locally)\n  - curl to 127.0.0.1 and to 10.200.0.7 with Host header -> HTTP 200\n  - curl to 20.200.0.2 -> HTTP 200 (backends reachable)\n- Ping/icmp from LB to web servers show ~1–2 ms latencies.\n\nConclusions\n- Network routing/infra (OSPF, DHCP relay, etc.) is functioning and not the root cause of observed HTTP performance.\n- The HTTP service is reachable and returns 200, but application-layer latency is significant: consistent TTFB ~0.28–0.32 s suggests load-balancer and/or backend web servers are introducing response delay.\n- Operational/configuration issues exist on the load balancer host: missing local DNS resolution for web99.local (getent empty) and potential confusion in addressing (inventory showing 10.200.0.x for web servers vs. nginx upstream set to 20.200.0.x). These inconsistencies increase risk and may complicate troubleshooting/healthchecks.\n- Root-cause candidates to investigate further (not remediations here):\n  - Backend application processing delay or initial connection setup delay on upstreams (backend web server processing time).\n  - Load balancer upstream/proxy behavior (connection setup, health check/retry behavior, upstream connection pooling) causing the ~300 ms TTFB.\n  - Local DNS/configuration on load_balancer (lack of DNS may affect health checks or internal tooling).\n\nIf you want, next steps I can run (upon your request) to further narrow the root cause:\n- Measure TTFB and response timings from the LB directly to each upstream backend (curl -w timing breakdown) to determine whether the backend itself introduces the ~300 ms before first byte.\n- Inspect nginx access/error logs and upstream healthcheck settings to see whether nginx is retrying or encountering slow upstreams.\n- Check backend web server application logs/timings to see server-side response times.\n- Verify FRR routing entries (show ip route) and interface addressing on server_access_router if you want the mapping between 10.200.0.x and 20.200.0.x clarified.\n\nEnd of report.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 11048, "output_tokens": 5481, "total_tokens": 16529, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 10368}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2816}}}
